10-03-2026
Great 👍 Let’s move to the 3rd SOLID principle.
Again we will follow the same 9-point structure we finalized earlier.
This principle was introduced by Barbara Liskov and later included in SOLID principles by Robert C. Martin.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)
________________________________________
1️⃣ Definition (Interview Ready)
Objects of a superclass should be replaceable with objects of its subclasses without breaking the correctness of the program.
In simple terms:
A child class must behave like its parent class.
If subclass changes expected behavior → LSP violation.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Core Idea
LSP ensures correct inheritance usage.
Many developers misuse inheritance.
Bad inheritance leads to:
•	runtime errors
•	unexpected behavior
•	broken polymorphism
LSP ensures:
Parent reference
      ↓
Child object substitution
      ↓
Program still works correctly
Example:
Bird bird = new Sparrow();
bird.fly();
If we replace Sparrow with another bird, program should still work.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Real-World Analogy
Think about electric power sockets.
Any device can be plugged in:
•	phone charger
•	laptop charger
•	TV cable
All devices follow the same socket standard.
If one device requires special socket, substitution fails.
That would violate LSP.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Bad Design Example (LSP Violation)
Classic example: Rectangle and Square
class Rectangle {

    protected int width;
    protected int height;

    public void setWidth(int width) {
        this.width = width;
    }

    public void setHeight(int height) {
        this.height = height;
    }

    public int getArea() {
        return width * height;
    }
}


Now subclass:
class Square extends Rectangle {

    public void setWidth(int width) {
        this.width = width;
        this.height = width;
    }

    public void setHeight(int height) {
        this.width = height;
        this.height = height;
    }
}


Now run:
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Rectangle rect = new Square();

        rect.setWidth(5);
        rect.setHeight(10);

        System.out.println(rect.getArea());
    }
}


Expected result:
50
Actual result:
100
Why?
Because Square changes behavior of Rectangle.
This breaks LSP.
________________________________________
5️⃣ Refactored Design (Correct Approach)
Instead of inheritance, use abstraction.
interface Shape {
    int getArea();
}


Rectangle:
class Rectangle implements Shape {

    private int width;
    private int height;

    public Rectangle(int width, int height) {
        this.width = width;
        this.height = height;
    }

    public int getArea() {
        return width * height;
    }
}


Square:
class Square implements Shape {

    private int side;

    public Square(int side) {
        this.side = side;
    }

    public int getArea() {
        return side * side;
    }
}


Main class:
public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Shape rect = new Rectangle(5,10);
        Shape square = new Square(5);

        System.out.println(rect.getArea());
        System.out.println(square.getArea());
    }
}


Output
50
25
Now substitution works correctly.
________________________________________
6️⃣ Advantages in Enterprise Systems
LSP improves system reliability.
Benefits:
1️⃣ Safe polymorphism
Child objects behave correctly.
________________________________________
2️⃣ Prevents fragile inheritance
Bad inheritance structures cause large production bugs.
________________________________________
3️⃣ Improves maintainability
Developers can replace implementations safely.
________________________________________
4️⃣ Supports clean architecture
Interfaces + abstraction avoid incorrect inheritance.
________________________________________
7️⃣ Common Interview Traps
Trap 1
Thinking LSP = inheritance
Wrong.
LSP ensures correct inheritance usage.
________________________________________
Trap 2
Ignoring behavior changes
Even if method signatures match, behavior may break.
________________________________________
Trap 3
Overusing inheritance
Often composition is better than inheritance.
________________________________________
8️⃣ Relation with Spring Architecture
Frameworks like **Spring Boot rely heavily on polymorphism.
Example:
PaymentService
     ↓
StripePaymentService
PaypalPaymentService
RazorpayPaymentService
Each implementation can replace another without breaking logic.
That is LSP in action.
Example:
PaymentService service = new StripePaymentService();
Later:
PaymentService service = new PaypalPaymentService();
Application should still behave correctly.
________________________________________
9️⃣ Scenario-Based Interview Question
Interview Question
Suppose you have a Bird class with a fly() method.
Then you create subclasses:
•	Sparrow
•	Eagle
•	Penguin
How will you design this system?
________________________________________
❌ Bad Design
class Bird {
    void fly() {}
}
Penguin cannot fly.
If we write:
class Penguin extends Bird {

    void fly() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }
}
This breaks LSP.
________________________________________
✅ Correct Design
Separate flying behavior.
interface Bird {}
Flying birds:
interface FlyingBird {
    void fly();
}
Sparrow:
class Sparrow implements Bird, FlyingBird {

    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Sparrow flying");
    }
}
Penguin:
class Penguin implements Bird {

    public void swim() {
        System.out.println("Penguin swimming");
    }
}
Now design is LSP compliant.
________________________________________
Interview-Ready Answer
Liskov Substitution Principle states that objects of a subclass should be replaceable with objects of the superclass without affecting the correctness of the program. This ensures that inheritance is used properly and subclasses do not break expected behavior.
________________________________________
✅ Next principle is Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).
Before moving forward, if you want, I can also show you one very tricky LSP interview question that many senior developers answer incorrectly.
Great 👍 Let’s look at a tricky LSP interview question.
Many experienced developers answer this incorrectly, so understanding the reasoning is important.
The principle originates from Barbara Liskov and was later included in SOLID by Robert C. Martin.
________________________________________
Tricky LSP Interview Question
Interviewer Scenario
You have a Bird class.
class Bird {
    void fly() {
        System.out.println("Bird is flying");
    }
}
Subclasses:
class Sparrow extends Bird {}
class Eagle extends Bird {}
class Penguin extends Bird {}
________________________________________
Question
Is this design correct or incorrect according to Liskov Substitution Principle?
Most developers answer:
"Yes, it is correct because Penguin is also a Bird."
But this answer is wrong.
________________________________________
Why This Design Violates LSP
A Penguin cannot fly.
But the parent class forces every bird to support:
fly()
If we implement Penguin like this:
class Penguin extends Bird {

    void fly() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException("Penguins cannot fly");
    }
}
Now consider this code:
public class Main {

    public static void makeBirdFly(Bird bird) {
        bird.fly();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Bird bird = new Penguin();
        makeBirdFly(bird);
    }
}
Program crashes.
Output:
Exception in thread "main"
UnsupportedOperationException
This means:
Penguin cannot safely replace Bird.
So substitution fails, which violates LSP.
________________________________________
Correct Design (LSP-Compliant)
Instead of forcing all birds to fly, separate behaviors.
Step 1 — Base abstraction
interface Bird {}
________________________________________
Step 2 — Flying capability
interface FlyingBird {
    void fly();
}
________________________________________
Step 3 — Implement classes
Sparrow:
class Sparrow implements Bird, FlyingBird {

    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Sparrow flying");
    }
}
Eagle:
class Eagle implements Bird, FlyingBird {

    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Eagle flying");
    }
}
Penguin:
class Penguin implements Bird {

    public void swim() {
        System.out.println("Penguin swimming");
    }
}
Now the design is correct because:
•	Only birds that can fly implement FlyingBird
•	Penguins are not forced to implement fly()
This follows LSP.
________________________________________
Runnable Example
public class Main {

    public static void makeBirdFly(FlyingBird bird) {
        bird.fly();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        FlyingBird sparrow = new Sparrow();
        makeBirdFly(sparrow);

        FlyingBird eagle = new Eagle();
        makeBirdFly(eagle);

        Penguin penguin = new Penguin();
        penguin.swim();
    }
}
Output
Sparrow flying
Eagle flying
Penguin swimming
No crashes.
System respects LSP.
________________________________________
What Interviewers Are Actually Testing
When asking this question, interviewers check if you understand:
Concept	Why
Inheritance misuse	Common design problem
Behavior compatibility	Core of LSP
Abstraction design	Senior developer skill
Interface segregation	Related SOLID principle
________________________________________
Senior-Level Interview Answer
If interviewer asks:
Why is the Bird–Penguin example an LSP violation?
Strong answer:
Because the subclass Penguin cannot fulfill the behavioral contract of the parent class Bird, specifically the fly() method. When a subclass cannot support the behavior expected by the base class, substituting it breaks program correctness, which violates the Liskov Substitution Principle.
________________________________________
Important Insight
Many developers think LSP is about:
IS-A relationship
But LSP is actually about:
Behavioral compatibility
A subclass must not change the expected behavior of the parent class.
________________________________________
✅ Next SOLID principle is Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).
It is closely related to the Bird example we just saw.
If you want, I can show something very useful next:
A simple rule that helps instantly detect LSP violations during design reviews.

Great 👍 Let’s learn a simple rule to instantly detect Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) violations during design reviews or interviews.
This principle originates from Barbara Liskov and is part of SOLID introduced by Robert C. Martin.
________________________________________
Simple Rule to Detect LSP Violations
When reviewing inheritance, ask this question:
Can the child class replace the parent class everywhere without changing program behavior?
If the answer is NO, then the design violates LSP.
________________________________________
Quick Checklist (Very Useful in Interviews)
Look for these 3 red flags.
________________________________________
🚩 Red Flag 1 — UnsupportedOperationException
If a subclass throws this:
throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
Example:
class Penguin extends Bird {

    void fly() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }
}
This means:
The subclass cannot support the parent behavior.
This is a clear LSP violation.
________________________________________
🚩 Red Flag 2 — Empty Method Implementation
Example:
class Penguin extends Bird {

    void fly() {
        // do nothing
    }
}
This is also bad because:
•	Parent expects flying behavior
•	Child silently ignores it
Still an LSP violation.
________________________________________
🚩 Red Flag 3 — Changing Expected Behavior
Example:
Parent:
withdraw(amount)
Child:
withdraw(amount) {
   if(amount > 1000)
      throw exception
}
Now substitution may break existing code.
Behavior is not compatible anymore.
________________________________________
Example from Real Enterprise Systems
Consider payment gateway abstraction.
interface PaymentProcessor {
    void processPayment();
}
Good implementations:
StripePaymentProcessor
PaypalPaymentProcessor
RazorpayPaymentProcessor
Each class behaves correctly when substituted.
Frameworks like **Spring Boot rely heavily on this concept.
You can replace implementations without breaking application logic.
________________________________________
Quick Mental Model for LSP
When designing inheritance, always think:
Parent defines contract
       ↓
Child must honor contract
       ↓
Behavior must remain valid
________________________________________
One-Line Rule (Senior Developer Trick)
This line impresses interviewers:
If a subclass needs to disable or alter the parent behavior, inheritance is probably wrong.
Use composition instead.
________________________________________
Another Classic LSP Violation Example
Bad design:
Vehicle
   |
Car
Bike
Bicycle
If Vehicle defines:
startEngine()
But Bicycle has no engine → LSP violation.
Correct design:
Vehicle
   |
EngineVehicle
   |      |
Car     Bike
Bicycle remains separate.
________________________________________
Why LSP Is Important
Without LSP:
•	polymorphism breaks
•	systems become fragile
•	bugs appear during runtime
With LSP:
•	safe substitution
•	predictable behavior
•	stable architecture
________________________________________
Interview Tip
If interviewer asks:
How do you detect LSP violation?
Best answer:
I check whether a subclass can replace the parent class without breaking program behavior. Common signs of violation include UnsupportedOperationException, empty method implementations, or behavior changes that break the parent contract.
________________________________________
✅ Next SOLID principle is Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).
Before we start ISP, there is one important relationship many senior developers miss:
LSP violations often happen because of bad interfaces.
That is exactly the problem ISP solves.
If you're ready, we can start Interface Segregation Principle (ISP).

